ation|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority Control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Byrd, Richard Evelyn}}\n\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1957 deaths]]\n[[Category:Aviators from Virginia]]\n[[Category:American navigators]]\n[[Category:Flight navigators]]\n[[Category:Explorers of Antarctica]]\n[[Category:American Episcopalians]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Burials at Arlington National Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Congressional Gold Medal recipients]]\n[[Category:United States and the Antarctic]]\n[[Category:Byrd family of Virginia|Richard Evelyn Byrd]]\n[[Category:United States Navy World War II admirals]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Aviators]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Navy Cross (United States)]]\n[[Category:United States Navy Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American oceanographers]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Navy rear admirals (upper half)]]\n[[Category:National Aviation Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia people]]\n[[Category:Virginia Military Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Winchester, Virginia]]\n[[Category:American polar explorers]]\n[[Category:20th-century explorers]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Navy Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia alumni]]\n[[Category:American Polar Society honorary members]]\n[[Category:Non-combat recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:Sons of the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from Beacon Hill, Boston]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Silver Buffalo Award]]\n", "name_user": "Igrallert", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:added link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_E._Byrd"}
{"title_page": "Sir David Cunningham, 1st Baronet, of Robertland", "text_new": "'''Sir David Cunningham, 1st Baronet of Robertland''' was the grandson of [[David Cunninghame of Robertland]], [[Master of Work to the Crown of Scotland]] for [[James VI of Scotland]]. [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] made him a Baronet of [[Nova Scotia]] on 25 November 1630, by [[Letters Patent]] to him and his heirs male whatsoever.\n\n[[Castle and Barony of Robertland|Robertland]] is located near [[Stewarton]], in the old district of Cunninghame, and is now part of [[East Ayrshire]], Scotland.\n\nA number of letters to him from his older cousin Sir [[David Cunningham, 1st Baronet of Auchinhervie|David Cunningham]] of [[Auchenharvie Castle|Auchenharvie]] survive in the [[National Archives of Scotland]]. In 1633 Auchenharvie bought clothes in London for Robertland to wear in Edinburgh during the coronation visit of King Charles in 1633, following the colours and styles of clothes made by the king's tailor Patrick Black. On 1 May 1633 Auchenharvie wrote:<blockquote>\"Now you shall expect a very rich cloth of silver doublet with black satin breeches and satin cloak much laced as the fashion is. This suit is for all great days and holly days and when for variety you please to make this suit somewhat worse there is a black satin doublet suitable, also you shall have another fair new kind of wrought satin suit willow colour with silver lace doublet breeches and cloak, to which for change and variety your satin doublet will suit very well, you shall have stockings, garters, roses, points, girdles, hat bands, and some few facing bands to make you complete, they will cost you dear enough.\"<ref>Maria Hayward, ''Stuart Style'' (Yale, 2020), pp. 182-3, National Records of Scotland GD237/25/2 no. 11.</ref></blockquote>\n\nDavid Cunningham married Elizabeth Jousie in 1637, daughter of the Edinburgh textile merchant and royal financier [[Robert Jousie]], and widow of the goldsmith James Heriot (d. 1634) a brother of [[George Heriot]].\n\nLike his father, Sir James Cunningham of Robertland, Gentleman of the Bedchamber to King Charles I, Sir David was a zealous [[cavalier]], and in the subsequent civil wars he suffered much on account of his loyalty to his monarch.\n\nHe was succeeded by his son, [[David Cunningham, 2nd Baronet of Robertland]], Commissioner of Supply for [[Ayrshire]].\n\n==References==\n*{{Rayment-bt|date=March 2012}}\n* ''The Scottish Nation'', by William Anderson, 1867 edition, volume 3, p.&nbsp;746.\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cunningham, Sir David, 1st Baronet}}\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Cavaliers]]\n[[Category:People from Ayrshire]]\n[[Category:Clan Cunningham|David]]\n\n\n{{baronet-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Sir David Cunningham, 1st Baronet of Robertland''' was the grandson of [[David Cunninghame of Robertland]], [[Master of Work to the Crown of Scotland]] for [[James VI of Scotland]]. [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] made him a Baronet of [[Nova Scotia]] on 25 November 1630, by [[Letters Patent]] to him and his heirs male whatsoever.\n\nA number of letters to him from his older cousin Sir [[David Cunningham, 1st Baronet of Auchinhervie|David Cunningham]] of [[Auchenharvie Castle|Auchenharvie]] survive in the [[National Archives of Scotland]]. In 1633 Auchenharvie bought clothes in London for Robertland to wear in Edinburgh during the coronation visit of King Charles in 1633, following the colours and styles of clothes made by the king's tailor Patrick Black. On 1 May 1633 Auchenharvie wrote:<blockquote>\"Now you shall expect a very rich cloth of silver doublet with black satin breeches and satin cloak much laced as the fashion is. This suit is for all great days and holly days and when for variety you please to make this suit somewhat worse there is a black satin doublet suitable, also you shall have another fair new kind of wrought satin suit willow colour with silver lace doublet breeches and cloak, to which for change and variety your satin doublet will suit very well, you shall have stockings, garters, roses, points, girdles, hat bands, and some few facing bands to make you complete, they will cost you dear enough.\"<ref>Maria Hayward, ''Stuart Style'' (Yale, 2020), pp. 182-3, National Records of Scotland GD237/25/2 no. 11.</ref></blockquote>\n\nDavid Cunningham married Elizabeth Jousie in 1637, daughter of the Edinburgh textile merchant and royal financier [[Robert Jousie]], and widow of the goldsmith James Heriot (d. 1634) a brother of [[George Heriot]].\n\nLike his father, Sir James Cunningham of Robertland, Gentleman of the Bedchamber to King Charles I, Sir David was a zealous [[cavalier]], and in the subsequent civil wars he suffered much on account of his loyalty to his monarch.\n\nHe was succeeded by his son, [[David Cunningham, 2nd Baronet of Robertland]], Commissioner of Supply for [[Ayrshire]].\n\n==References==\n*{{Rayment-bt|date=March 2012}}\n* ''The Scottish Nation'', by William Anderson, 1867 edition, volume 3, p.&nbsp;746.\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cunningham, Sir David, 1st Baronet}}\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Cavaliers]]\n[[Category:People from Ayrshire]]\n[[Category:Clan Cunningham|David]]\n\n\n{{baronet-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "Robertland", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_David_Cunningham,_1st_Baronet,_of_Robertland"}
{"title_page": "Teddy Brayshaw", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Teddy Brayshaw\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = Edward Brayshaw\n| birth_date     =  {{birth date|1863|10|6|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Sheffield]], England\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1908|11|20|1863|10|6|df=y}}\n| death_place    = \n| height         = \n| position       = [[Defender (association football)|Centre half]]\n| years1         = \n| clubs1         = All Saints\n| caps1          = \n| goals1         = \n| years2         = \n| clubs2         = Walkley\n| caps2          = \n| goals2         = \n| years3         = 1884\u20131891\n| clubs3         = [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|The Wednesday]]\n| caps3          = 0\n| goals3         = 0\n| years4         = 1892\u20131893\n| clubs4         = [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]]\n| caps4          = 2\n| goals4         = 0\n| years5         = 1893\n| clubs5         = Chesterfield Rangers\n| caps5          = \n| goals5         = \n| totalcaps      = \n| totalgoals     = \n| nationalyears1 = 1887\n| nationalteam1  = [[England national football team|England]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n}}\n'''Edward Brayshaw''' (6 October 1863 \u2013 20 November 1908)<ref name=\"englandfootballonline\" /> was an English international [[association football|footballer]], who played as a [[Defender (association football)|centre half]].\n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Sheffield]], Brayshaw played for [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|The Wednesday]] and [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]]<ref name=Joyce>{{cite book |last=Joyce |first=Michael |title=Football League Players' Records 1888 to 1939 |publisher=SoccerData |location=Nottingham |year=2004 |page=35 |isbn=978-1-899468-67-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Lamming|first1=Douglas|title=A who's who of Grimsby Town AFC : 1890-1985|date=1985|publisher=Hutton|location=Beverley|isbn=